.TH "rvt_create_qp" 9 "rvt_create_qp" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
rvt_create_qp \- create a queue pair for a device
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "struct ib_qp *" rvt_create_qp
.BI "(struct ib_pd *ibpd "  ","
.BI "struct ib_qp_init_attr *init_attr "  ","
.BI "struct ib_udata *udata "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "ibpd" 12
the protection domain who's device we create the queue pair for
.IP "init_attr" 12
the attributes of the queue pair
.IP "udata" 12
user data for libibverbs.so
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Queue pair creation is mostly an rvt issue. However, drivers have their own
unique idea of what queue pair numbers mean. For instance there is a reserved
range for PSM.

Called by the \fBib_create_qp\fP core verbs function.
.SH "RETURN"
the queue pair on success, otherwise returns an errno.
